  "cited": {
    "headline": "Effective pass rate under one percent. The triennial examination seated thirty-three from a national field, while the largest documented sittings drew more than two hundred thousand applicants.",
    "detail": "The regular triennial examination (siknyeonsi) seated thirty-three passers nationally, narrowed from a nationwide preliminary quota of 240 down to thirty-three at the final palace stage. Applicant totals were not centrally kept, but surviving records show the scale. A single celebratory examination in 1800, held for the crown prince's investiture, drew 215,417 applicants over two days, with 111,838 sitting on the first day. Against thirty-three seats, the effective pass rate at a sitting of that size was a small fraction of one percent. The under-one-percent figure is an estimate read from the fixed seat count and the largest documented applicant figures, since no continuous applicant register survives.",
